    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Limits to a Compromise</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Leida Snow letter about Mar 25 article on computerized Broadway show music says it is a good option for schools with small budgets, but not Broadway (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>As a former theater critic (1010 WINS Radio) and former Drama Desk president, I welcome the availability of computer-enhanced orchestras on the road and in schools. Giving audiences of all ages the opportunity to hear something approximating a full complement of musicians if their only option is tape or a truncated orchestra seems worth the downside. The same reasoning does not apply to Broadway productions however. People come from all over the world to Broadway, and they want something they can't get at home. It should be live theater, with a live orchestra in the pit.</p>
        <p>Leida Snow  Manhattan</p>
      </block>
